oseph81", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDevelopment:fixing tense)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Baker_and_the_Beauty"}
{"title_page": "Stampa (family)", "text_new": "{{Royal house||surname=Stampa|coat of arms=Coat of arms of the Stampa family.jpg|motto='''Specimen virtutis avit\u00e6'''|country=[[Italy]]|titles=[[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] <br/> [[Marquess]] of [[Parona]] <br/> [[Count]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Melzo]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Rivolta d'Adda]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Montecastello]]  <br/> [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]] <br/> [[Lord]] of [[Tromello]]|founder=Carlo Lanfranco Stampa|founding year=[[8th century]]|cadet branches=Casati Stampa di Soncino <br/> Stampa-de Leyva <br/> Stampa di Parona  <br/> Stampa di Ferentino|created by=[[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]|coat_of_arms_size=100px}}<br />[[File:IMG 6689 - Milano - Torre di Palazzo Stampa di Soncino - Foto Giovanni Dall'Orto - 8-Mar-2007.jpg|thumb|[[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palazzo Stampa di Soncino]] in [[Milan]]]]\nThe '''Stampa''' are a well-know family of old [[Nobility of Italy|Italian nobility]] that rose to prominence in the [[15th century|15th century.]] They were [[Grandees of Spain]], members the [[Order of the Golden Fleece|Order]] [[Order of the Golden Fleece|of the Golden Fleece]] and owned many estates throughout the [[Italian Peninsula|Italian peninsula]], including a [[Soncino's Castle|Castle]] in [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]], a [[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palace]] in [[Milan|Milan,]] and countless others in [[Muggi\u00f2]], [[Melzo]], [[Gorgonzola, Milan|Gorgonzola]], [[Rivolta d'Adda]], [[Ferentino]] and [[Rome]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it/cgi-bin/siusa/pagina.pl?TipoPag=prodfamiglia&Chiave=27423|title=SIUSA - Stampa|website=siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>. They are related to some of the most important Italian noble [[Nobility|houses]], such as the [[Doria (family)|Doria]], [[House of Sforza|Sforza]], [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] and [[Visconti of Milan|Visconti]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lombardiabeniculturali.it/archivi/soggetti-produttori/famiglia/MIDD0002B3/|title=Stampa, famiglia (sec. XV - sec. XVIII) \u2013 Archivi storici \u2013 Lombardia Beni Culturali|website=www.lombardiabeniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>. \n\n== Early History ==\n[[File:Soncino Castle.jpg|thumb|The Soncino Castle, formerly called ''Castello Sforzesco'', was donated to the Stampa family by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. ]]\nSome historians trace their ancestry back to Carlo Lanfranco [[Lord]] of [[\u00c9tampes]], later governor of [[Milan]] under [[Charlemagne]]. These sources argue that the Stampa settled in [[Milan]] and [[Gravedona]], ruling over the [[Val Bregaglia]] and much of the surrounding regions. The best evidence for this would be the city of [[Stampa]], named so by the family in honour of its ancestors<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC/page/n276 271]|quote=stefano stampa atene.|title=Notizie storiche intorno al comune di Gravedona ed alle principali sue famiglie dai tempi pi\u00f9 remoti fino al 1865|last=Stampa|first=Giuseppe|date=1866|publisher=D. Salvi|language=it}}</ref>.  \n\nOthers, such as the Count and historian Pompeo Litta, do not believe these sources, arguing that it was very common for aristocratic families to trace their ancestry back to [[France]]. One of the earliest documents Litta could find dates back to [[1277]], when the [[Archbishop of Milan|Archbishop]] [[Ottone Visconti]] became [[List of rulers of Milan|Lord of Milan]]; it consists in a list compiled by Ottone himself, granting several privileges to the most influential families of the city, including Arrigo Stampa . \n\nThe Stampa decided the destiny of Milan on more than one occasion. The first time was in [[1450]], when they helped [[Francesco I Sforza]] become [[Duke of Milan]]. In [[February]] the Venetians had sent an ambassador, Leonardo Venieri, to negotiate the city's surrender and help them defeat Sforza. Giovanni Stampa marched onto Milan with his army and killed Venieri on the stairs of [[Royal Palace of Milan|Palazzo Ducale]], forcing the milanese to surrender. The [[Duke]] was naturally obliged to the family, and rewarded them with many honours<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\n== Stampa di Soncino ==\nIn [[1536]] Massimiliano Stampa was created [[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]. The family ruled over [[Milan]] until [[1876]], and the city flourished immensely under their guidance. Massimiliano Cesare Stampa, the last Marquess of Soncino, died without children and donated his [[Soncino's Castle|castle]] to the [[Soncino, Lombardy|city]]. His title and assets were then taken over by the Casati family, thus creating a new branch called Casati Stampa di Soncino'''.''' \n\n==== Marques of Soncino Stampa (1536-1876) ====\n\n* '''Massimiliano I''' ([[1536]]-[[1543]]), Count, then 1st Marquess of Soncino from 1536\n* '''Ermes I''' ([[1543]]-[[1557]]), Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano I\n* '''Massimiliano II''' ([[1557]]-[[1596]]), 3rd  Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes I. Married to Marianna de Leyva, aunt of [[The Nun of Monza|Suor Virginia de Leyva]]\n* '''Ermes II''' ([[1596]]-[[1621]]), 4th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano II\n* '''Massimiliano III''' ([[1621]]-[[1659]]), 5th Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes II, sentenced to death for murder\n* '''Giovanni I''' ([[1659]]-[[1678]]), 6th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano III\n* '''Massimiliano IV''' ([[1678]]-[[1693]]), 7th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giovanni I\n* '''Giuseppe I''' ([[1693]]-[[1735]]), 8th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano IV\n* '''Massimiliano V Giovanni''' ([[1735]]-[[1769]]), 9th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giuseppe I\n* '''Massimiliano VI Giuseppe''' (1769-1818), 10th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano V Giovanni, [[Grandee|Grandee of Spain]] e Member of the [[Order of the Iron Crown]], married to Carlotta [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] in 1785\n* '''Massimiliano VII Giovanni''' ([[1818]]-[[1824]]), 11th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VI Giuseppe\n* '''Massimiliano VIII''' ([[1824]]-[[1834]]), 12th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VII Giovanni\n* '''Massimiliano IX Giovanni''' ([[1834]]-[[1876]]), 13th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VIII and last Marquess of Soncino\n\n: ''After Massimiliano IX Giovanni's death, the Casati inherited the title of Marquess of Soncino, which was held unofficially by Camillo Casati Stampa from 1876 to 1892''\n\n==== Casati Stampa, Marquess of Casate (1876-1970) ====\n\n* '''Camillo I''', Marquess of Casate ([[1892]]-[[1946]]), husband of [[Luisa Casati]].\n* '''Camillo II''', Marquess of Casate ([[1946]]-[[1970]]), son of Camillo I. His infamous suicide marked the end of the dynasty.<ref>Franco Avenia, ''IL MARCHESE, LA MOGLIE, L'AMANTE, ECCO LA CHIAVE SCIENTIFICA DI UN MEMORABILE DELITTO'', da: \"l'attimo fuggente\", 2008 {{Cite web|url=http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|title=Copia archiviata|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130132925/http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|archivedate=30 November 2010|accessdate=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Stampa di Ferentino ==\n[[File:Palazzo Stampa di Ferentino.jpg|alt=Palazzo Stampa|thumb|Palazzo dei Conti Stampa di Ferentino in [[Rome]]]]\nIn the early years of the [[18th century]] the Count Pietro Antonio Stampa of Milan settled in [[central Italy]] and married a [[noblewoman]] from [[Frosinone]]. In [[1779]] Pietro's youngest son Angelo was created [[First|1st]] [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Libro d'Oro della Nobilt\u00e0 Italiana|publisher=|year=1921|isbn=|location=|pages=440}}</ref> with the consent of [[Pope Pius VI]]. He and his brother Filippo had been serving the [[History of the papacy|papacy]] since [[Pope Clement XIV]] appointed them state administrators of the [[Duchy of Castro]] in [[1770]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.ferentino.fr.it/index.php?id_sezione=669|title=Famous citizens of Ferentino (Filippo Stampa)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nAmong their many properties the Stampa had [[Elba]], an island in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], which they administered since [[Pope Gregory VII|Gregory VII]] granted them the concession on the mine caves. When [[Napoleon]] conquered [[Elba]] and seized the mines, [[Pope Pius VII]] offered the count Domenico Stampa an important job within the [[Papal State|Papal States]] to compensate him for the financial damage he suffered. The [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Pope Pius IX|Mastai Ferretti]] (later [[Pope Pius IX]]) also ensured that Domenico contracted a good marriage with Paolina Vinciguerra, the last heir of the count Antonini di [[Alatri]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Appunti personali del Conte Filippo Maria Stampa|last=Stampa|first=Filippo M.|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\nThe family continues to exist in [[Rome]] and [[Milan]].\n\n== Notable members ==\n\n* Massimiliano Stampa I, [[Politician]]\n* Stefano Stampa, [[Writer]] and [[stepson]] of [[Alessandro Manzoni]]\n*[[Gaspara Stampa]], [[16th century]] [[poetess]].\n*[[Carlo Gaetano Stampa]], [[Archbishop of Milan]]\n* Massimiliano IX Giovanni, [[Patriot]]\n*[[Ermete Stampa]], [[Bishop of Novara]]\n* Giorgio Stampa, [[Discalced Carmelite]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stampa (family)}}\n\n[[Category:Noble families]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n", "text_old": "{{Royal house||surname=Stampa|coat of arms=Coat of arms of the Stampa family.jpg|motto='''Specimen virtutis avit\u00e6'''|country=[[Italy]]|titles=[[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] <br/> [[Marquess]] of [[Parona]] <br/> [[Count]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Melzo]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Rivolta d'Adda]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Montecastello]]  <br/> [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]] <br/> [[Lord]] of [[Tromello]]|founder=Carlo Lanfranco Stampa|founding year=[[8th century]]|cadet branches=Casati Stampa di Soncino <br/> Stampa-de Leyva <br/> Stampa di Parona  <br/> Stampa di Ferentino|created by=[[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]|coat_of_arms_size=100px}}<br />[[File:IMG 6689 - Milano - Torre di Palazzo Stampa di Soncino - Foto Giovanni Dall'Orto - 8-Mar-2007.jpg|thumb|[[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palazzo Stampa di Soncino]] in [[Milan]]]]\nThe '''Stampa''' are a well-know family of old [[Nobility of Italy|Italian nobility]] that rose to prominence in the [[15th century|15th century.]] They were [[Grandees of Spain]], members the [[Order of the Golden Fleece|Order]] [[Order of the Golden Fleece|of the Golden Fleece]] and owned many estates throughout the [[Italian Peninsula|Italian peninsula]], including a [[Soncino's Castle|Castle]] in [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]], a [[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palace]] in [[Milan|Milan,]] and countless others in [[Muggi\u00f2]], [[Melzo]], [[Gorgonzola, Milan|Gorgonzola]], [[Rivolta d'Adda]], [[Ferentino]] and [[Rome]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it/cgi-bin/siusa/pagina.pl?TipoPag=prodfamiglia&Chiave=27423|title=SIUSA - Stampa|website=siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>. They are related to some of the most important Italian noble [[Nobility|houses]], such as the [[Doria (family)|Doria]], [[House of Sforza|Sforza]], [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] and [[Visconti of Milan|Visconti]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lombardiabeniculturali.it/archivi/soggetti-produttori/famiglia/MIDD0002B3/|title=Stampa, famiglia (sec. XV - sec. XVIII) \u2013 Archivi storici \u2013 Lombardia Beni Culturali|website=www.lombardiabeniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>. \n\n== Early History ==\n[[File:Soncino Castle.jpg|thumb|The Soncino Castle, formerly called ''Castello Sforzesco'', was donated to the Stampa family by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. ]]\nSome historians trace their ancestry back to Carlo Lanfranco [[Lord]] of [[\u00c9tampes]], later governor of [[Milan]] under [[Charlemagne]]. These sources argue that the Stampa settled between [[Milan]] and [[Gravedona]], ruling over the [[Val Bregaglia]] and much of the surrounding regions. The best evidence for this would be the city of [[Stampa]], named so by the family in honour of its ancestors<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC/page/n276 271]|quote=stefano stampa atene.|title=Notizie storiche intorno al comune di Gravedona ed alle principali sue famiglie dai tempi pi\u00f9 remoti fino al 1865|last=Stampa|first=Giuseppe|date=1866|publisher=D. Salvi|language=it}}</ref>.  \n\nOthers, such as the Count and historian Pompeo Litta, do not believe these sources, arguing that it was very common for aristocratic families to falsely attribute their origins to [[France]]. One of the earliest documents Litta could find dates back to [[1277]], when the [[Archbishop of Milan|Archbishop]] [[Ottone Visconti]] became [[List of rulers of Milan|Lord of Milan]]; it consists in a list compiled by Ottone himself, granting several privileges to the most influential families of the city, including Arrigo Stampa . \n\nThe Stampa decided of the destiny of Milan on more than one occasion. The first time was in [[1450]], when they helped [[Francesco I Sforza]] become [[Duke of Milan]]. In [[February]] the Venetians had sent an ambassador, Leonardo Venieri, to negotiate the city's surrender and help them defeat Sforza. Giovanni Stampa marched onto Milan with his army and killed Venieri on the stairs of [[Royal Palace of Milan|Palazzo Ducale]], forcing the milanese to surrender to Francesco I. The newly elected [[Duke]] was naturally obliged to the family, and rewarded them with many honours<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\n== Stampa di Soncino ==\nIn [[1536]] Massimiliano Stampa was created [[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]. The family ruled over [[Milan]] until [[1876]], and the city flourished immensely under their guidance. Massimiliano Cesare Stampa, the last Marquess of Soncino, died without children and donated his [[Soncino's Castle|castle]] to the [[Soncino, Lombardy|city]]. His title and assets were then taken over by the Casati family, thus creating a new branch called Casati Stampa di Soncino'''.''' \n\n==== Marques of Soncino Stampa (1536-1876) ====\n\n* '''Massimiliano I''' ([[1536]]-[[1543]]), Count, then 1st Marquess of Soncino from 1536\n* '''Ermes I''' ([[1543]]-[[1557]]), Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano I\n* '''Massimiliano II''' ([[1557]]-[[1596]]), 3rd  Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes I. Married to Marianna de Leyva, aunt of [[The Nun of Monza|Suor Virginia de Leyva]]\n* '''Ermes II''' ([[1596]]-[[1621]]), 4th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano II\n* '''Massimiliano III''' ([[1621]]-[[1659]]), 5th Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes II, sentenced to death for murder\n* '''Giovanni I''' ([[1659]]-[[1678]]), 6th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano III\n* '''Massimiliano IV''' ([[1678]]-[[1693]]), 7th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giovanni I\n* '''Giuseppe I''' ([[1693]]-[[1735]]), 8th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano IV\n* '''Massimiliano V Giovanni''' ([[1735]]-[[1769]]), 9th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giuseppe I\n* '''Massimiliano VI Giuseppe''' (1769-1818), 10th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano V Giovanni, [[Grandee|Grandee of Spain]] e Member of the [[Order of the Iron Crown]], married to Carlotta [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] in 1785\n* '''Massimiliano VII Giovanni''' ([[1818]]-[[1824]]), 11th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VI Giuseppe\n* '''Massimiliano VIII''' ([[1824]]-[[1834]]), 12th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VII Giovanni\n* '''Massimiliano IX Giovanni''' ([[1834]]-[[1876]]), 13th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VIII and last Marquess of Soncino\n\n: ''After Massimiliano IX Giovanni's death, the Casati inherited the title of Marquess of Soncino, which was held unofficially by Camillo Casati Stampa from 1876 to 1892''\n\n==== Casati Stampa, Marquess of Casate (1876-1970) ====\n\n* '''Camillo I''', Marquess of Casate ([[1892]]-[[1946]]), husband of [[Luisa Casati]].\n* '''Camillo II''', Marquess of Casate ([[1946]]-[[1970]]), son of Camillo I. His infamous suicide marked the end of the dynasty.<ref>Franco Avenia, ''IL MARCHESE, LA MOGLIE, L'AMANTE, ECCO LA CHIAVE SCIENTIFICA DI UN MEMORABILE DELITTO'', da: \"l'attimo fuggente\", 2008 {{Cite web|url=http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|title=Copia archiviata|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130132925/http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|archivedate=30 November 2010|accessdate=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Stampa di Ferentino ==\n[[File:Palazzo Stampa di Ferentino.jpg|alt=Palazzo Stampa|thumb|Palazzo dei Conti Stampa di Ferentino in [[Rome]]]]\nIn the early years of the [[18th century]] the Count Pietro Antonio Stampa of Milan settled in [[central Italy]] and married a [[noblewoman]] from [[Frosinone]]. In [[1779]] Pietro's youngest son Angelo was created [[First|1st]] [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Libro d'Oro della Nobilt\u00e0 Italiana|publisher=|year=1921|isbn=|location=|pages=440}}</ref> with the consent of [[Pope Pius VI]]. He and his brother Filippo had been serving the [[History of the papacy|papacy]] since [[Pope Clement XIV]] appointed them state administrators of the [[Duchy of Castro]] in [[1770]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.ferentino.fr.it/index.php?id_sezione=669|title=Famous citizens of Ferentino (Filippo Stampa)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nAmong their many properties the Stampa had [[Elba]], an island in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], which they administered since [[Pope Gregory VII|Gregory VII]] granted them the concession on the mine caves. When [[Napoleon]] conquered [[Elba]] and seized the mines, [[Pope Pius VII]] offered the count Domenico Stampa an important job within the [[Papal State|Papal States]] to compensate him for the financial damage he suffered. The [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Pope Pius IX|Mastai Ferretti]] (later [[Pope Pius IX]]) also ensured that Domenico contracted a good marriage with Paolina Vinciguerra, the last heir of the count Antonini di [[Alatri]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Appunti personali del Conte Filippo Maria Stampa|last=Stampa|first=Filippo M.|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\nThe family continues to exist in [[Rome]] and [[Milan]].\n\n== Notable members ==\n\n* Massimiliano Stampa I, [[Politician]]\n* Stefano Stampa, [[Writer]] and [[stepson]] of [[Alessandro Manzoni]]\n*[[Gaspara Stampa]], [[16th century]] [[poetess]].\n*[[Carlo Gaetano Stampa]], [[Archbishop of Milan]]\n* Massimiliano IX Giovanni, [[Patriot]]\n*[[Ermete Stampa]], [[Bishop of Novara]]\n* Giorgio Stampa, [[Discalced Carmelite]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stampa (family)}}\n\n[[Category:Noble families]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n", "na